============================================================
GEOMETRIC DERIVATION OF THE COSMOLOGICAL ACTIVATION LAW
============================================================

1. Motivation

The phenomenological cosmological model uses an activation function
g(z) that modulates the effective matter contribution to the expansion
history. Empirically the activation law was found to be well described
by

    g(z) = 1 − exp[ − ( ln(1+z) / u_s )^ν ]

with parameters (u_s , ν) obtained from fits to cosmological data.

Here we show that this functional form follows directly from a simple
geometric construction based on cumulative expansion history.

The derivation does not require any assumptions about the detailed
microphysics of the curvature–memory sector.


------------------------------------------------------------
2. Cumulative expansion-history variable
------------------------------------------------------------

Consider the logarithmic expansion increment

    dU = d ln(1+z)

which measures differential cosmological expansion exposure.

Using

    d ln(1+z) = dz / (1+z)

the cumulative expansion exposure from the present epoch to redshift z
is

    U(z) = ∫₀ᶻ dz' / (1+z')

which integrates exactly to

    U(z) = ln(1+z).

The quantity U(z) therefore represents the total logarithmic expansion
experienced between redshift z and the present.


------------------------------------------------------------
3. Dimensionless loading variable
------------------------------------------------------------

Introduce a characteristic activation scale u_s and define the
dimensionless loading variable

    u(z) = U(z) / u_s
         = ln(1+z) / u_s.

The parameter u_s therefore represents the cumulative expansion
required for the onset of significant activation.


------------------------------------------------------------
4. Activation response law
------------------------------------------------------------

Assume that the inactive fraction of curvature–memory domains follows
a stretched–exponential survival law

    S(u) = exp( − u^ν )

where ν is a shape parameter describing the distribution of activation
thresholds.

The activated fraction is therefore

    g(u) = 1 − S(u)
         = 1 − exp( − u^ν ).


------------------------------------------------------------
5. Redshift activation function
------------------------------------------------------------

Substituting the cumulative expansion variable u(z) gives

    g(z) = 1 − exp[ − ( ln(1+z) / u_s )^ν ].

This reproduces exactly the empirical activation function used in the
cosmological fits.


------------------------------------------------------------
6. Equality–tied parametrisation
------------------------------------------------------------

If the activation scale is related to the matter–dark–energy equality
epoch through

    u_s = α u_eq

with

    u_eq = (1/3) ln( (1−Ω_m) / Ω_m ),

then the activation law becomes

    g(z) =
        1 − exp[
            − ( ln(1+z) /
                ( α (1/3) ln((1−Ω_m)/Ω_m) )
              )^ν
        ].


------------------------------------------------------------
7. Interpretation
------------------------------------------------------------

This derivation shows that the cosmological activation function is a
direct consequence of two ingredients:

    (i) cumulative expansion history

        U(z) = ln(1+z)

    (ii) stretched–exponential activation of a threshold ensemble

        g(U) = 1 − exp[ − (U/u_s)^ν ].

The activation variable is therefore a purely geometric quantity
derived from the integrated expansion history. The parameters (u_s , ν)
encode the distribution of activation thresholds within the
curvature–memory sector.


------------------------------------------------------------
8. Conceptual separation of roles
------------------------------------------------------------

The framework therefore naturally separates into two components:

    Cosmological sector:
        geometric cumulative activation
        U(z) = ln(1+z)

    Local dynamical sector:
        transport and dynamics of the curvature–memory field.

The cosmological activation law emerges independently of the detailed
field dynamics.
